04830nam a22005055i 9780773563278DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19921992xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735632787 a10.1515/97807735632782doi  a(DE-B1597)655431  a(OCoLC)732600989  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aKE4219.5 ǂb C357 1992eb 7aPOL0400002bisacsh04a342.71/0851 aCairns, Alan C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCharter versus Federalism :bThe Dilemmas of Constitutional Reform /cAlan C. Cairns. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1992] 4c©1992  a1 online resource (160 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tInternational Influences on the Charter -- tConstitutional Refashioning of Community -- tThe Charter and the Constitution Act, 1982 -- tThe Lessons of Meech Lake -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aResponding to the increasing diversity of the Canadian population -- and to an increasing sensitivity to historical diversities -- the 1982 Constitution Act amended the British North America Act and introduced the Charter of Rights and Freedoms, giving new powers to heterogeneous groups within the Canadian polity. These changes disturbed the equilibrium of an older, federalist Canada whose constitutional concerns were limited to the relative powers of federal and provincial governments and to French-English ethnic/linguistic questions. Cairns underlines the significance of international influences on the development of Canada's constitution, in particular the adoption of the Charter, and examines the constitution's role in shaping Canadians' civic identities and community conceptions. He argues that the constitution is a powerful mobilizing instrument that shapes the people subject to its authority. Canada is now populated by what Cairns calls "Charter Canadians," who see themselves as rights-bearers and tend to look to the federal government as the effective focus of political community. During the Meech Lake affair, the demands of Charter Canadians and politicized aboriginal peoples clashed with Quebec's constitutional aspirations as well as older élite accommodation politics. In addition to the Charter, the 1982 Constitution Act contained a new amending formula that contradicted the Charter's message that the rights of individuals precede those of governments. This formula gave a collective of federal and provincial governments a formal monopoly on constitutional change and encouraged the belief, refuted by the Meech Lake experience, that they could amend the constitution in terms of their own self-interest and announce the results as a fait accompli. The clash between the Charter and the amending formula is constitutionally destabilizing, Cairns argues, because these two parts of the same constitution are based on different understandings of the fundamental purpose of the constitution and for whose benefit it exists. The Meech Lake fiasco, having brought Canada to the brink of disaster, clearly indicates that Canada's future constitutional health depends not only on the reconciliation of Quebec with the rest of Canada but -- respectful of the Charter's message -- on a simultaneous constitutional rapprochement between citizens and governments in the process of constitutional reform.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010